                <head>56. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On October 2, 1958, the Republic of Guinea was established by proclamation of its
                    National Assembly. The text of a letter of November 1, 1958, from President
                        <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> to Prime Minister
                        <persName corresp="#p_TAS1">Sekou Touré</persName> extending formal U.S.
                    recognition is in <hi rend="italic">Public Papers of the Presidents of the
                        United States: <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Dwight D. Eisenhower</persName>,
                        1958</hi>, page 826. On February 16, 1959, the Department of State announced
                    the opening on February 13 of an embassy at Conakry, with <persName>Robert W.
                        Rinden</persName> as Chargé d’Affaires; see Department of State <hi
                        rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, March 16, 1959, page 390. The first U.S.
                    Ambassador to Guinea, <persName>John Howard Morrow</persName>, presented his
                    credentials on July 30.</p>
                <p>For further documentation on U.S. policy toward Guinea, see <ref target="#d305"
                        >Documents 305</ref>–<ref target="#d331">331</ref>.</p>
            </div>
